---
import TopNav from '../components/nav/TopNav.astro';
import WorkflowNav from '../components/nav/WorkflowNav.astro';
import MobileMenu from '../components/nav/MobileMenu.astro';
import SearchOverlay from '../components/nav/SearchOverlay.astro';
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <meta name="description" content="Why structured AI workflows, how the trust model works, and what the APS Prompt Gallery is for." />
  <link rel="icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Atkinson+Hyperlegible+Next:ital,wght@0,200..800;1,200..800&family=Lexend:wght@300..700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" />
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/fuse.js@7.0.0/dist/fuse.min.js"></script>
  <title>About – APS Prompt Gallery</title>
  <style>
    *, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }
    :root {
      --color-primary: #170a1c;
      --color-primary-light: #DFD9E2;
      --color-bg: #F7F7FF;
      --color-surface: #ffffff;
      --color-border: #dee2e6;
      --color-text: #212529;
      --color-muted: #6c757d;
      --radius: 8px;
      --font-heading: 'Lexend', sans-serif;
      --font-body: 'Atkinson Hyperlegible Next', sans-serif;
    }
    body { font-family: var(--font-body); background: var(--color-bg); color: var(--color-text); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
    h1, h2, h3 { font-family: var(--font-heading); }
    a { color: var(--color-primary); text-decoration: none; }
    a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
    .container { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 20px; }

    /* ── Page header ─────────────────────────────────── */
    .page-header {
      padding: 40px 0 32px;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
      margin-bottom: 40px;
    }
    .page-header h1 { margin: 0 0 10px; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--color-primary); }
    .page-header p { margin: 0; color: var(--color-muted); max-width: 620px; }

    /* ── Section headings ────────────────────────────── */
    .section-heading {
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      color: var(--color-muted);
      margin: 40px 0 16px;
      padding-bottom: 8px;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    }

    /* ── Prose sections ──────────────────────────────── */
    .prose-section {
      margin-bottom: 40px;
    }
    .prose-section h2 {
      font-size: 1.15rem;
      color: var(--color-primary);
      margin: 0 0 12px;
    }
    .prose-section p {
      margin: 0 0 14px;
      max-width: 680px;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .prose-section p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

    /* ── Trust level colours (shared with .maturity-stage-label) ── */
    .trust-high     { background: #d1e7dd; color: #0f5132; }
    .trust-medium   { background: #fff3cd; color: #664d03; }
    .trust-low      { background: #f8d7da; color: #58151c; }

    /* ── Maturity model ──────────────────────────────── */
    .maturity-intro {
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      color: var(--color-muted);
      margin: 0 0 20px;
      max-width: 640px;
    }
    .maturity-stages {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(180px, 1fr));
      gap: 12px;
      margin-bottom: 24px;
    }
    .maturity-stage-card {
      background: var(--color-surface);
      border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 14px 16px;
    }
    .maturity-stage-label {
      display: inline-block;
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.04em;
      padding: 2px 8px;
      border-radius: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }
    .ms-draft     { background: #e9ecef; color: #495057; }
    .ms-tested    { background: #fff3cd; color: #664d03; }
    .ms-reviewed  { background: #d1e7dd; color: #0f5132; }
    .ms-validated { background: #ede7f6; color: #4a235a; }
    .maturity-stage-desc {
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      color: var(--color-muted);
      margin: 0;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }
    .maturity-governance-note {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--color-muted);
      background: var(--color-surface);
      border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 12px 16px;
    }
  </style>
  <script data-goatcounter="https://deanhewson.goatcounter.com/count"
          async src="//gc.zgo.at/count.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
  <TopNav />
  <WorkflowNav />
  <MobileMenu />
  <div class="container">

    <div class="page-header">
      <h1>About</h1>
      <p>Why structured AI workflows, how the trust model works, and what the APS Prompt Gallery is for.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Opening -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <p>
        We hear a lot about what you can use AI for and whether it is appropriate.
        What has been missing is the practical how layer: how to prompt well for complex government work, how to verify
        outputs systematically, and how to build compliance checking into the process rather than bolting it on at the end.
      </p>
      <p>
        This project fills that gap. It provides structured, multi-step workflows for common APS tasks, with quality gates
        built in at each stage. Instead of giving you a single prompt and hoping for the best, each workflow breaks a task
        into steps where you can inspect, verify, and redirect the AI's output before moving on.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is free, open source, works with any AI tool your agency approves (Claude, ChatGPT, Copilot), and does not
        store any information you enter.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Why workflows -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <h2>Why workflows, not just prompts</h2>
      <p>
        A single prompt like "write me a briefing note" produces inconsistent results that depend entirely on the individual's
        prompting intuition. Two officers doing the same task get wildly different quality. Good approaches are not captured,
        shared, or improved.
      </p>
      <p>
        Workflows solve this by breaking complex tasks into a sequence of smaller steps, where the output of one becomes the
        input for the next. Each step has a specific purpose: research, structure, draft, verify, challenge, revise. This is
        how developers have been using AI for years. It produces better, more consistent results because each step is
        inspectable, and the officer can intervene at any point.
      </p>
      <p>
        The real value is in the quality gates: verification steps that challenge the AI's output before you rely on it.
        Claim verification extracts every factual claim and categorises it by reliability. Red-team review stress-tests the
        draft from a sceptical senior executive perspective. Compliance checks run the output against PGPA Act, PSPF,
        Privacy Act, and APS Values requirements. These are not optional extras. They are the accountability layer that
        makes AI-assisted work defensible.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Trust model -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <h2>The trust model</h2>
      <p>
        The hardest part of using AI in government is not generating text. It is knowing how much to trust what it produces.
        A well-formatted briefing note looks equally polished whether the underlying facts are real or hallucinated. This
        creates two failure modes: over-trust (rubber-stamping AI output without verification) and under-trust (rejecting
        AI entirely after one bad experience).
      </p>
      <p>Every step in every workflow carries an explicit trust level:</p>
      <div class="maturity-stages">
        <div class="maturity-stage-card">
          <span class="maturity-stage-label trust-high">High trust</span>
          <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Structuring, formatting, brainstorming, summarising content you provided. Use with light review.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="maturity-stage-card">
          <span class="maturity-stage-label trust-medium">Medium trust</span>
          <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Drafting prose, identifying issues, stakeholder analysis. Use as a starting point; verify key claims.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="maturity-stage-card">
          <span class="maturity-stage-label trust-low">Low trust</span>
          <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Specific statistics, legislative references, current events, program details. Always independently verify.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        Quality gates are mapped to trust levels. Low-trust outputs require claim verification. Medium-trust outputs should
        go through completeness and bias checks. High-trust outputs may only need a tone and audience review. The goal is
        to make the trust boundary impossible to miss, so officers can make informed decisions about what to verify and
        how much effort to invest.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Maturity model -->
    <div class="section-heading">Workflow maturity</div>
    <p class="maturity-intro">
      Each workflow carries a maturity stage that tells you how much confidence you can place in its design.
      This is separate from whether a workflow is published – it tracks how thoroughly it's been tested and reviewed.
      You'll see the maturity badge on each workflow card and at the top of each workflow page.
    </p>

    <div class="maturity-stages">
      <div class="maturity-stage-card">
        <span class="maturity-stage-label ms-draft">Draft</span>
        <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Structure and prompts exist but haven't been systematically tested against real APS tasks. Use with extra scrutiny.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="maturity-stage-card">
        <span class="maturity-stage-label ms-tested">Tested</span>
        <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Run through representative scenarios by the maintainer or early users. Prompt sequences work and outputs are usable. No independent review yet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="maturity-stage-card">
        <span class="maturity-stage-label ms-reviewed">Reviewed</span>
        <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Reviewed by at least one subject-matter practitioner outside the original author. Confirmed sound for its stated domain and audience.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="maturity-stage-card">
        <span class="maturity-stage-label ms-validated">Validated</span>
        <p class="maturity-stage-desc">Tested by practitioners across multiple agencies, with feedback incorporated. Represents genuine cross-agency confidence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="maturity-governance-note">
      Maturity progresses as the project grows: Draft and Tested are sole-maintainer stages.
      Reviewed requires a trusted practitioner reviewer. Validated requires feedback from multiple agencies.
      <a href="/roadmap">See where each workflow currently sits →</a>
    </p>

    <!-- Compliance by design -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <h2>Compliance by design</h2>
      <p>
        APS work operates under specific accountability frameworks that do not apply to general productivity. Under the
        PGPA Act, officers are accountable for the advice they provide. Under the PSPF, information must be handled
        according to its classification. The Privacy Act and Australian Privacy Principles govern personal information.
        APS Values require impartiality, ethical conduct, and commitment to service.
      </p>
      <p>
        These are not afterthoughts in the Gallery. Compliance checks are embedded as standard workflow steps. Every
        workflow that produces advice or analysis includes a compliance gate that reviews the output against relevant
        frameworks. The prompts themselves are designed with classification awareness: they are built for OFFICIAL-level
        work using public AI tools, and they include explicit guidance about what not to include.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Who this is for -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <h2>Who this is for</h2>
      <p>
        The workflows are designed for APS staff at any level across policy, program delivery, stakeholder engagement,
        and general productivity domains. Each workflow adapts to your experience level:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Getting started:</strong> simplified workflow with fewer steps, copy-paste-ready prompts, and clear
        guidance on what to do with each output.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Full workflow:</strong> the complete multi-step sequence with all quality gates.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Expert mode:</strong> advanced options including parallel analysis chains, custom role definitions, and
        iterative verification loops.
      </p>
      <p>
        Your AI prompting skill and your domain expertise are separate things. A senior EL2 policy expert who is new to
        AI tools needs different support than an APS 5 who has been experimenting with Claude for months. The skill level
        toggle controls the prompting complexity, but your domain judgement is what makes every quality gate output
        valuable. The workflows are designed so that AI does the drafting and stress-testing, and you bring the expertise
        and accountability.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- About the project -->
    <div class="prose-section">
      <h2>About the project</h2>
      <p>
        This is an independent, side-of-desk project built by Dean Hewson at the Parliamentary Budget Office. It is not
        an official Australian Government resource and does not represent the views of any agency.
      </p>
      <p>
        The project is open source under CC BY 4.0. The source code and all workflow content are available on
        <a href="https://github.com/deanhewson/public-service-prompt-gallery" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
        Contributions are welcome from APS staff across agencies, whether that is suggesting a new workflow, improving
        an existing one, or reporting something that does not work. See the
        <a href="https://github.com/deanhewson/public-service-prompt-gallery/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">contribution guide</a>
        or the <a href="/workflow-guide">workflow structure guide</a> for how to get involved.
      </p>
      <p>
        The longer-term vision is community ownership. A library like this is most valuable when it reflects real work
        across agencies, not one person's perspective. If your agency is interested in forking the library for internal
        use, running it behind Entra ID authentication on Azure Static Web Apps, or contributing domain-specific
        workflows, get in touch via
        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/deanhewson" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a> or
        <a href="https://github.com/deanhewson/public-service-prompt-gallery" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
  <SearchOverlay />
</body>
</html>
